<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{ko-}}}} demonstratives generally relate to something near to the speaker, either physically or emotionally.
</p>

<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{so-}}}} demonstratives generally relate to something near to the listener. They can be used to
refer to something that is not close to either the speaker or the listener if information about that
thing has already been provided.
</p>

<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{a-}}}} demonstratives generally relate to something that is not near to either the speaker
or the listener.
</p>

<p>
The @HI{{@EM{{do-}}}} demonstratives refer to something about which a question is being asked.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kore">@HI{{@EM{{kore}}}}</a>, @HI{{@EM{{sore}}}} and @HI{{@EM{{are}}}} are 
demonstratives and function as pronouns.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kore}}}} refers to something or someone near the speaker.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{kore}}wo kudasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Please give me this one.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sore}}}} refers to something or someone near the listener.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{sore}}ha}}@KJ{{resign}}@KJ{{write}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Is that a dictionary?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{are}}}} refers to something or someone far from both the speaker and the listener.
</p>

<p>
<a name="dore">@HI{{@EM{{dore}}}}</a> is an interrogative used to ask the listener to choose one item from a set of <em>three</em> or more things.
</p>


@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kono">@HI{{@EM{{kono}}}}</a>, @HI{{@EM{{sono}}}} and @HI{{@EM{{ano}}}} are
pre-noun adjectivals and serve to modify a noun. @HI{{@EM{{dono}}}} is used with a following noun to ask "which" noun.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{kono}}}} refers to a thing or a person near the speaker.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{kono}}}}@KJ{{book}}@HI{{ha}}@KJ{{private}}@HI{{nodesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This book is mine.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{sono}}}} refers to a thing or a person near the listener.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ano}}}} refers to a thing or a person far from both the speaker and the listener.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@EM{{ano}}@FG{{@KJ{{direction}}:kata}}hadonatadesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Who is that (person)?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KT{{santosu}}@HI{{sanha @EM{{dono}}}}@KJ{{person}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Which one is Mr. Santos?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="donna">@HI{{@EM{{donnna}}}}</a> is used with a following noun to mean "what kind of". 
It can also be used to ask the listener to name one of a group which the following noun describes describes.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @KJ{{nara}}@KJ{{good}}@HI{{ha @EM{{donnna}}}}@KJ{{village}}@HI{{desuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What kind of town is Nara?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@EM{{donna}}@KT{{supotsu}}gasukidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @KT{{sakka-}}@HI{{gasukidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: What sports do you like?
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: I like football.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="koko">@HI{{@EM{{koko}}}}</a>, @HI{{@EM{{soko}}}} and @HI{{@EM{{asoko}}}} refer to a place.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="kochira">@HI{{@EM{{kochira}}}}</a>, @HI{{@EM{{sochira}}}} and @HI{{@EM{{achira}}}} are demonstratives
that refer to a direction. They can also be used to refer to a place, in which case they are considered more
polite than @HI{{@EM{{koko}}}}, @HI{{@EM{{soko}}}} and @HI{{@EM{{asoko}}}}.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="doko">@HI{{@EM{{doko}}}}</a> means "where" and @HI{{@EM{{dochira}}}} means "which direction".
@HI{{@EM{{dochira}}}} can also mean "where", in which case it is more polite than
@HI{{@EM{{doko}}}}. <br/>
@HI{{@EM{{doko}}}} or @HI{{@EM{{dochira}}}} are also used to ask the name of a country, school,
company or any place or organisation to which a person belongs. @HI{{nann}} cannot be
used for this purpose.
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="a-conv">@HI{{a}}- demonstratives can also refer to something that has cropped up in conversation or appears in a text.
They refer to something directly known to both the speaker and the listener.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{sakki,@FG{{@KJ{{mountain^book}}:yamamoto}}san'ni@FG{{@KJ{{meeting}}:a}}ttayo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{e,@EM{{ano}}@FG{{@KJ{{person}}:hito}},@KJ{{now^day^book}}niirundesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: I met Mr. Yamamoto just now.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Oh? Is he in Japan now?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="so-conv">@HI{{so}}- demonstratives can also refer to something that has cropped up in conversation or appears in a text.
They refer to something known only to the speaker or only to the listener.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{sakki,@FG{{@KJ{{map^write^Bldg.}}:toshokan'}}de@KT{{maria}}santoiu@KJ{{person}}ni@KJ{{meeting}}ttandakedone.
      @EM{{sono}}@KJ{{person}},kono@KJ{{study^exam}}de@KJ{{day^book^go}}wo@KJ{{exertion^strong}}shitandatte.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{soudesuka.@EM{{sono}}@KJ{{person}}ha@KJ{{what^year-end}}guraidesuka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: I met someone called Maria in the library just now. She said she had studied Japanese at this school.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: Really? How old is she?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="so-written">@HI{{so}}- demonstratives in writing can refer to the previous sentence.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{igirisu}}no@FG{{@KJ{{person^spirit}}:ninki}}@FG{{@KJ{{little^explanation}}:shousetsu}}ga
      @KJ{{day^book^word}}ni@FG{{@KJ{{flip^translate}}:hon'yaku}}saremashita.
      @EM{{sore}}ga@FG{{@KJ{{now^year}}:kotoshi}}@KJ{{day^book}}de@KT{{besutosera-}}ninarimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A popular English novel was translated into Japanese. Now it's become a bestseller in Japan this year.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="ko-context">@HI{{ko}}- demonstratives in a sentence can refer to something that appears later.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@FG{{@KJ{{new^hear}}:shinbin'}}ni@EM{{kon'na}}kotoga@KJ{{write}}iteatta.@FG{{@KJ{{utmost^near}}:saikin'}}no@KJ{{day^book^person}}ha@FG{{@KJ{{house^tribe}}:kazoku}}min'nade
      @FG{{@KJ{{rest^day}}:kyuujitsu}}ni@KT{{konpyu-ta-ge-mu}}wo@FG{{@KJ{{music}}:tano}}shimusouda.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This was written in a newspaper. "Apparently Japanese families these days enjoy playing computer games together on their days off."
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<a name="ko-vs-so"></a>
In writing a word from the @HI{{ko}}-series may be used rather than one from the @HI{{so}}-series to
refer to something previously mentioned. In this case the author is describing something
as though it really existed then and there.

<p>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ashitagaichiban'@KJ{{longing}}shii@KJ{{thing}}ha[dokodemo @KT{{doa}}]desu.
      @EM{{kono}}@KT{{doa}}wo@KJ{{open}}keruto,dokodemo@KJ{{going}}kitai 
      @KJ{{place}}he@KJ{{going}}kemasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What I want most is a "magic door". When you open this door, you can go anywhere you want.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

